Tensors are numerical encoded representations of structured/unstructured input data

Any kind of input, e it image, audio, etc can be converted into Tensors

In a neural network, the input data that we feed needs to exist in numerical form, as a neural network does not understand whole images, or any audio recording, 

But if we can numerically encode it and feed it to a Neural network, the Neural network can then process and learn specific types of features (patterns from that input)

Tensors are those numerical representations, and thus tensors are the main type of data that we use when working with Neural Networks


A Vector is a Tensor of Rank 1, since we only need 1 basis vector per component (x,y,z,.... components) to represent a vector space

A Scalar is a Tensor of Rank 0

A 3*3 Matrix is a Rank 2 Tensor

A Rank 3 matric might look like a Cube (A 2D Array)

